e%20still%20getting%20your%20work%20in%2C%20or%20not%20working%20but%20keeping%20your%20mouse%20moving%20to%20appear%20as%20if%20you're%20online%20in%20hopes%20that%20no%20one%20will%20notice%20your%20drop%20in%20productivity.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOn%20the%20one%20hand%2C%20this%20sounds%20like%20an%20awesome%2C%20novel%20possibility%20brought%20about%20by%20the%20rise%20of%20remote%20work.%20Responding%20to%20the%2010th%20email%20of%20the%20day%20while%20sipping%20a%20margarita%20on%20the%20beach%20sounds%20a%20lot%20nicer%20than%20doing%20it%20from%20an%20office%20desk%20as%20a%20coworker%20nearby%20munches%20loudly%20on%20their%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fin-defense-sad-salad-opinion-2020-3%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Esad%20salad%3C%2Fa%3E.%20If%20work%20gets%20slow%20in%20the%20summer%2C%20there's%20no%20good%20reason%20to%20sit%20and%20stare%20at%20your%20computer.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOn%20the%20other%20hand%2C%20the%20idea%20that%20people%20are%20under%20so%20much%20pressure%20at%20work%20that%20they%20feel%20they%20can't%20take%20true%20disconnect-from-everything%20time%20off%20or%20even%20tell%20their%20boss%20they're%20working%20out%20of%20town%20for%20a%20bit%20is%20deeply%20depressing.%20It's%20a%20stark%20reminder%20of%20how%20broken%20American%20work%20culture%20is%2C%20just%20in%20time%20for%20summer.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIt%20may%20be%20a%20question%20of%20just%20psychological%20safety%2C%20or%20lack%20thereof%2C%20that%20the%20employee%20doesn't%20feel%20like%20they%20can%20openly%20have%20a%20conversation%20with%20their%20manager%20about%20taking%20real%20time%20off%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Rebecca%20Zucker%2C%20an%20executive%20coach%20and%20the%20founding%20partner%20of%20Next%20Step%20Partners%2C%20a%20leadership%20consultancy.%20%26quot%3BWe're%20all%20big%20boys%20and%20girls%2C%20and%20it's%20a%20question%20of%20not%20where%20we're%20working%20or%20when%20we're%20working%2C%20in%20terms%20of%20the%20hours%20we're%20working%2C%20but%20are%20we%20doing%20what%20we%20need%20to%20get%20done.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20whole%20quiet-vacationing%20discourse%20got%20kicked%20up%20by%20a%20recent%20Harris%20Poll%20survey%20on%20out-of-office%20culture.%20It%20found%20that%2028%25%20of%20workers%20said%20they'd%20taken%20time%20off%20work%20without%20telling%20their%20bosses%20%E2%80%94%20basically%2C%20they're%20out%20of%20the%20office%2C%20but%20not%20%26quot%3Bofficially.%26quot%3B%20Millennials%20in%20particular%20have%20picked%20up%20on%20the%20practice%2C%20with%2037%25%20saying%20they'd%20dipped%20out%20of%20work%20on%20the%20sly.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIt's%20not%20that%20these%20workers%20are%20unhappy%20with%20the%20vacation%20their%20companies%20offer%3A%2083%25%20of%20respondents%20said%20they%20were%20satisfied%20with%20their%20company's%20paid-time-off%20policy.%20The%20issue%20seems%20to%20be%20that%20employees%20don't%20feel%20like%20they%20can%20actually%20use%20the%20time%20off%20they're%20given.%20Eight%20in%2010%20workers%20said%20they%20didn't%20use%20the%20maximum%20amount%20of%20PTO%20allowed%3B%20some%20said%20they%20felt%20pressure%20to%20always%20be%20available%2C%20while%20others%20cited%20a%20heavy%20workload%20as%20their%20reason.%20Almost%20half%20said%20they%20got%20nervous%20about%20requesting%20time%20away%2C%20and%20three-quarters%20said%20they%20wished%20their%20workplace%20culture%20put%20more%20value%20on%20taking%20breaks.%20Workers%20reported%20being%20tricky%20about%20the%20whole%20thing%2C%20too%3A%20About%20a%20third%20said%20they%20moved%20their%20mouse%20to%20make%20it%20look%20like%20they%20were%20online%2C%20and%20about%20the%20same%20share%20said%20they%20scheduled%20messages%20outside%20work%20hours%20to%20give%20the%20impression%20that%20they%20were%20working%20overtime.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20problem%20isn't%20really%20that%20people%20are%20working%20from%20elsewhere%2C%20especially%20if%20it's%20not%20hurting%20their%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fremote-work-wfh-productivity-impact-no-consensus-goldman-sachs-2023-8%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eproductivity%3C%2Fa%3E.%20The%20greater%20issue%20is%20what%20it%20signifies%20about%20their%20relationship%20with%20work%20and%20the%20incentives%20that%20have%20been%20fostered%20at%20their%20companies.%20People%20feeling%20like%20they%20have%20to%20be%20sneaky%20about%20their%20whereabouts%20is%20not%20a%20positive%20sign%2C%20nor%20is%20feeling%20like%20the%20only%20way%20to%20disconnect%20is%20to%20remain%20half%20plugged%20in.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20people%20taking%20vacations%20on%20the%20sly%20may%20be%20at%20organizations%20that%20are%20likelier%20to%20reward%20overworkers%2C%20said%20Malissa%20Clark%2C%20an%20associate%20professor%20and%20the%20head%20of%20the%20Healthy%20Work%20Lab%20at%20the%20University%20of%20Georgia.%20In%20turn%2C%20those%20quiet%20vacations%20may%20perversely%20reinforce%20the%20always-on%20culture%2C%20even%20when%20always%20being%20on%20isn't%20necessary%20or%20leading%20to%20better%20business%20results.%20Clark%2C%20who%20also%20wrote%20the%20book%20%26quot%3BNever%20Not%20Working%3A%20Why%20the%20Always-On%20Culture%20Is%20Bad%20for%20Business%20%E2%80%94%20and%20How%20to%20Fix%20It%2C%26quot%3B%20pointed%20to%202015%20research%20looking%20at%20how%20some%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fmen-pretending-to-be-working-2015-5%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Emen%20at%20a%20consulting%20firm%3C%2Fa%3E%20were%20able%20to%20pull%20back%20from%20work%20while%20pretending%20to%20still%20put%20in%2080-hour%20weeks.%20Their%20managers%20couldn't%20tell%20the%20difference%2C%20and%20they%20were%20rewarded%20for%20giving%20off%20the%20impression%20that%20they%20were%20workaholics%2C%20whereas%20men%20who%20were%20up%20front%20about%20needing%20to%20downshift%20were%20penalized.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThat's%20why%20there's%20this%20pressure%20for%20people%20to%20constantly%20be%20working%20and%20feel%20like%20if%20they%20take%20a%20step%20back%20they'll%20be%20left%20behind%2C%20because%20that's%20a%20very%20real%20thing%2C%26quot%3B%20Clark%20said.%20%26quot%3BApparently%2C%20that's%20what%20a%20lot%20of%20organizations%20reward.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EPretending%20to%20work%20when%20you're%20not%20or%20acting%20like%20you're%20putting%20in%20more%20hours%20than%20you%20do%20is%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwall-street-star-blackrock-manager-burnout-work-job-success-happiness-2023-5%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Enot%20a%20new%20phenomenon%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Zucker%20recalled%20working%20years%20ago%20at%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fquit-wall-street-investment-banking-after-fainting-bad-work-culture-2024-4%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ean%20investment%20bank%3C%2Fa%3E%20where%20men%20would%20leave%20their%20suit%20jackets%20on%20the%20backs%20of%20their%20chairs%20after%20hours%20so%20people%20would%20think%20they%20were%20still%20somewhere%20in%20the%20office.%20But%20technology%20does%20make%20this%20behavior%20easier.%20The%20ability%20to%20connect%20from%20anywhere%20is%20a%20double-edged%20sword%3A%20Sure%2C%20it's%20nice%20to%20be%20able%20to%20answer%20an%20email%20on%20a%20midday%20walk%20or%20work%20from%20a%20relative's%20house%20over%20the%20holidays%2C%20but%20it%20sucks%20to%20know%20your%20boss%20knows%20that%20you%20saw%20that%2010%20p.m.%20Slack%20message%20pop%20up%20on%20your%20phone.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThis%20is%20a%20societal%20problem%20and%20one%20that%20is%20uniquely%20American.%20We're%20told%20to%20go%2C%20go%2C%20go%2C%20made%20to%20feel%20like%20we%20can%20never%20get%20off%20the%20treadmill%20for%20even%20a%20second%2C%20lest%20we%20fall%20behind%20or%20give%20the%20impression%20that%20we're%20not%20trying%20hard.%20We%20often%20don't%20see%20taking%20time%20off%20as%20necessary%20and%20well%20deserved%20but%20as%20a%20sign%20of%20laziness%20and%20lack%20of%20work%20ethic.%20People%20aren't%20told%20to%20work%20to%20live%3B%20they're%20told%20to%20live%20to%20work.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Cp%3ESome%20of%20the%20fundamentals%20underlying%20quiet%20vacationing%20are%20positive.%20We%20live%20in%20an%20era%20where%20a%20lot%20of%20people%20can%20work%20from%20wherever%20and%20have%20more%20flexibility%20to%20achieve%20a%20better%20work-life%20balance.%20The%20rub%20is%20the%20sneakiness%20of%20it%20all.%20It%20would%20be%20much%20better%20if%20we%20were%20talking%20about%2C%20say%2C%20%26quot%3Bloud%20working%20from%20anywhere%20for%20a%20month%2C%26quot%3B%20or%20whatever%20you'd%20want%20to%20call%20it.%20(Or%20we%20could%20stop%20coining%20terms%20for%20work%20trends%2C%20the%20true%20dream.)%20It%20should%20be%20OK%20to%20have%20a%20conversation%20with%20your%20manager%20about%20spending%20a%20few%20days%20in%20the%20mountains%20or%20on%20the%20beach%20and%2C%20as%20long%20as%20the%20WiFi%20is%20decent%2C%20fulfilling%20your%20capitalist%20soldier%20duties.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EClark%20said%20this%20trend%20may%20make%20employers%20even%20more%20eager%20to%20force%20workers%20back%20to%20the%20office.%20Managers%20don't%20always%20love%20the%20idea%20that%20they%20don't%20know%20where%20their%20employees%20are%2C%20and%20they%20have%20the%20(often%20false)%20impression%20that%20being%20out%20of%20sight%20means%20not%20working.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWorking%20from%20elsewhere%20does%20not%20erase%20the%20need%20for%20an%20actual%20vacation.%20There's%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwhy-americans-should-take-their-vacation-days-2015-6%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eall%20sorts%20of%20research%3C%2Fa%3E%20indicating%20that%20time%20off%20improves%20mental%20and%20physical%20health%2C%20reduces%20stress%2C%20and%20boosts%20productivity%2C%20among%20other%20benefits.%20Even%20%3Cem%3Eplanning%20%3C%2Fem%3Ea%20vacation%20makes%20people%20happier.%20People%20need%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fvacation-health-benefits-2018-8%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Epsychologically%20detach%20from%20work%20%3C%2Fa%3Ein%20order%20to%20relax%20and%20recover.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BBy%20always%20feeling%20like%20you%20have%20to%20stay%20connected%2C%20you%20never%20recover%20from%20work%2C%26quot%3B%20Clark%20said.%20%26quot%3BAnd%20so%20it's%20like%20you're%20constantly%20running%20a%20marathon%2C%20but%20then%20you%20never%20take%20a%20break%2C%20and%20what%20is%20it%20going%20to%20do%3F%20It's%20going%20to%20wear%20your%20body%20down%20slowly%2C%20gradually%2C%20to%20the%20point%20where%20you%20hit%20a%20wall.%20And%20then%20all%20of%20a%20sudden%20you're%20burnt%20out.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20you're%20quiet%20vacationing%20and%20your%20boss%20doesn't%20know%2C%20good%20for%20you%2C%20I%20guess.%20But%20it%20would%20probably%20be%20better%20if%20you%20could%20be%20honest%20about%20where%20you%20are%20and%20what%20you're%20doing.%20And%20none%20of%20this%20scraps%20the%20need%20for%20an%20actual%20vacation.%20Regardless%20of%20how%20up%20front%20(or%20not)%20employees%20are%2C%20at%20the%20end%20of%20the%20day%2C%20American%20work%20culture%20is%20the%20bad%20guy%20here.%20The%20toxicity%20of%20hustle%20culture%20is%20the%20real%20problem%2C%20not%20the%20person%20who's%20low-key%20working%20from%20a%20cabin%20in%20the%20woods%20or%20the%20coworker%20who%20said%20screw%20it%20and%20is%20taking%20three%20weeks%20off.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fauthor%2Femily-stewart%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3E%3Cu%3EEmily%20Stewart%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cem%3E%20is%20a%20senior%20correspondent%20at%20Business%20Insider%2C%20writing%20about%20business%20and%20the%20economy.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.busi